Then the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\mathbf{v}$ is
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v},\]and the projection of $\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ onto $\mathbf{v}$ is
\[\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{v}} \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v}.\]Since both of these projections are $\mathbf{p},$
\begin{align*}
\frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v} &= \mathbf{p}, \\
\frac{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v} &= \mathbf{p}.
\end{align*}Then
\[\frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v} - \frac{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}.\]Then
\[\left( \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} - \frac{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} \right) \mathbf{v} = \mathbf{0}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2} = \frac{\begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}}{\|\mathbf{v}\|^2}.\]Then
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \mathbf{v}.\]Solving, we find $\mathbf{v} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 2 \end{pmatrix}}.$

