Solution:
We have that $\tan \theta_1 = \frac{y}{x} = \frac{\theta_1}{3}$ and $\tan \theta_2 = \frac{y}{x} = \frac{\theta_2}{9}.$  Then $\theta_1 = 3 \tan \theta_1$ and $\theta_2 = 9 \tan \theta_2.$  Also,
\[\tan \theta_1 - \tan \theta_2 = \frac{\sin (\theta_1 - \theta_2)}{\cos \theta_1 \cos \theta_2} = \frac{1}{\cos \theta_1 \cos \theta_2},\]so
\[\frac{\theta_1}{3} - \frac{\theta_2}{9} = \frac{1}{\cos \theta_1 \cos \theta_2}.\]From $\theta_1 - \theta_2 = \frac{\pi}{2},$ $\cos (\theta_1 - \theta_2) = 0,$ so
\[\cos \theta_1 \sin \theta_2 - \sin \theta_1 \cos \theta_2 = 0.\]Then $\sin (\theta_1 - \theta_2) = 0,$ so $\theta_1 - \theta_2 = k \pi$ for some integer $k.$  But $\theta_1 - \theta_2 = \frac{\pi}{2},$ so $k$ must be odd.  Therefore, $k = 1,$ so $\theta_1 - \theta_2 = \pi.$

